]] at [[TCU Horned Frogs men's basketball|TCU]] before transferring to [[Santa Ana College]], a junior college in California where he was a first-team All-State selection. In 1991 he joined the [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|University of Cincinnati]], and with the Bearcats he reached the Final Four during the [[1992 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1992 NCAA Tournament]]. After going undrafted in the [[1993 NBA draft]] he played for various [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]] teams and abroad in [[South Korea]] and [[Taiwan]]. He also earned two selections in the [[United States men's national basketball team|United States national team]]: he won the silver medal at the [[1995 Pan American Games]] and the gold medal during the [[1997 Tournament of the Americas]]. After retiring as a player he has held several assistant coach jobs, mainly for [[Bob Huggins]], first at [[Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball|Kansas State]] and later at West Virginia.\n\n== High school career ==\nMartin is a native of [[West Covina, California]], and he attended [[Whittier Christian High School]] in nearby [[La Habra, California|La Habra]], where he played as a [[center (basketball)|center]]<ref name=leader>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-01-08-sp-23007-story.html|title=Getting It Together : Whittier Christian\u2019s Martin Grows Up to Become Team Leader|author=Killion, Ann|date=January 8, 1988|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> and [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-03-06-sp-4834-story.html|title=SOUTHERN SECTION BOYS\u2019 BASKETBALL CHAMPIONSHIP GAMES : 1-A : Crossroads vs. Whittier Christian|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=March 6, 1987|author=Gruppie, Guy|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> A starter since his sophomore year,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-12-01-sp-25771-story.html|title=PREP BASKETBALL PREVIEW : THE PLAYERS: : Adam Keefe, Woodbridge Center, Is Alone at the Top|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|author=Lowery, Steve|date=December 1, 1987|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> in his junior season Martin averaged 21.9 points and 14.1 rebounds per game, earning the Most Valuable Player award in the 1-A league and was selected in the All-Southern and All-State First Teams.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1987-12-02-sp-17347-story.html|title=Whittier Christian\u2019s Still the One : Martin\u2019s Return Makes Cuccia\u2019s Team Tough to Beat|author=Ludovise, Barbie|date=December 2, 1987|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=team88>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30022674/the_los_angeles_times/|title=The Times' All-Southeast High School Boys Basketball Team Packs Scoring Punch|author=Snyder, Don|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=April 14, 1988|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> Martin was again selected as first-team all-state for his senior year, during which he averaged 24.1 points per game.<ref name=team88 /> During his time at Whittier Christian, Martin was an honor student.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1992-03-24-1992084033-story.html|title=Cincinnati sees NCAA tourney as proving ground Team full of transfers, unknowns seeks respect|author=Markus, Don|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=March 24, 1992|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== College career ==\nMartin signed to play for [[TCU Horned Frogs men's basketball|TCU]] in February 1988,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Horned Frogs' coach is happy with his team|newspaper=[[Baxter Bulletin]]|date=February 24, 1988|page=10}}</ref> having already signed a [[National Letter of Intent|letter of intent]] in the previous months.<ref name=leader /> Under head coach [[Moe Iba]], Martin [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his true freshman season in 1988\u201389<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-03-06-sp-337-story.html|title=Despite Limelight, Martin Focuses on Game|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|author=Kresal, Steve|date=March 6, 1991|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> and received limited playing time in the 1989\u201390 season as a 6-foot-5, 198-pound freshman;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://repository.tcu.edu/bitstream/handle/116099117/16997/19880415.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y\n|title=Basketball continues signing|newspaper=TCU Daily Skiff|date=April 15, 1988|page=4|author=Hargrove, Randy|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> at the end of the season he had appeared in all 29 games played by the team, starting 7 of them, and he had posted averages of 6.9 points, 4.3 rebounds and 1.4 assists in 15.2 minutes per game; he was the 4th best rebounder and the 6th best scorer on his team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/texas-christian/1990.html|title=1989-90 TCU Horned Frogs Roster and Stats|website=sports-reference.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn April 1990 Martin announced that he was leaving TCU and transferring to another school;<ref>{{Cite news|title=UALR's Newell gets Lamar basketball job|newspaper=[[The Daily News (Texas)|The Daily News]]|date=April 6, 1990|page=22}}</ref> he chose [[Santa Ana College]] (which at the time was called Rancho Santiago Junior College).<ref name=meet>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28416540/the_cincinnati_enquirer/|title=Meet the Bearcats|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=March 24, 1992|page=1|via=Newspapers.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> While at Rancho Santiago, Martin averaged 22.5 points (832 total) and 9.4 rebounds per game over 37 games (he averaged 25 points per game over 12 games of conference play), and established a program record for highest field goal percentage in a seasion with 63.7%.<ref name=dons>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacdons.com/hof/members/members/martin|title=Hall of Fame - Erik Martin - Men's Basketball, Class of 2006|website=sacdons.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the season Rancho Santiago won the state championship, and Martin was selected in the All-State first team.<ref name=dons /> In 2006 Martin was inducted in the Santa Ana College Hall of Fame.<ref name=dons />\n\nIn 1991 Martin and junior college teammate [[Corie Blount]] decided to transfer to [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]].<ref name=meet /> Martin and Blount were recruited by assistant coach Steve Moeller, who had brought to the Bearcats other junior college players: [[Nick Van Exel]], Terry Nelson and [[Herb Jones (basketball)|Herb Jones]] (who had transferred to Cincinnati in 1990).<ref>{{Cite news|title=UC assistant sought for head-coaching jobs|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|date=April 6, 1992|author=Groeschen, Tom|page=48}}</ref> Martin chose jersey number 3<ref name=meet /> and in his first year with his new team he played in all 34 games of the season, being employed off the bench by coach [[Bob Huggins]]: he averaged 6.3 points and 4 rebounds while playing 16.4 minutes per game, and he was the 5th best scorer on the team, the 3rd best rebounder (behind Jones and Blount), and the 3rd best shotblocker (0.5 per game).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/cincinnati/1992.html|title=1991-92 Cincinnati Bearcats Roster and Stats|website=sports-reference.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> The Bearcats experienced a successful season and won the [[Great Midwest Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Great Midwest Conference Tournament]], gaining access to the [[1992 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]]: Martin played all 5 games of the tournament, averaging 7.4 points and 5.8 rebounds, and during the Final Four he recorded a double-double of 10 points and 10 rebounds against [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] in a tournament-high 30 minutes of play.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/erik-martin-1/gamelog/1992/|title=Erik Martin 1991-92 Game Log|website=sports-reference.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMartin stayed at Cincinnati also for his senior season in 1992\u201393. On December 11, 1992, in a game against [[Southeast Missouri State Redhawks men's basketball|Southeast Missouri State]], Martin shot 10-for-11 from the field (90.9%), recording the 2nd-best shooting performance in Cincinnati history at the time.<ref name=guide72>''2016\u201317 Cincinnati Basketball Media Guide'', 2016, p. 72.</ref> On January 27, 1993 Martin recorded a career-high 6 steals against [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier]].<ref name=guide72 /> Martin ended the season averaging 13.5 points, 6.7 rebounds and 1.4 assists in 27.1 minutes per game, having started all 31 games. He ranked 2nd on the team in scoring behind Van Exel, and was the team leader in rebounds and blocks per game;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/cincinnati/1993.html|title=1992-93 Cincinnati Bearcats Roster and Stats|website=sports-reference.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> that year he also led the conference in field goal percentage with 60.3%. Cincinnati again qualified for the [[1993 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]], and Martin played all 4 games, recording a tournament-high 21 points against [[New Mexico State Aggies men's basketball|New Mexico State]] on March 21, and played 42 minutes against [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]] on March 28, posting 16 points and 6 rebounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/erik-martin-1/gamelog/1993/|title=Erik Martin 1992-93 Game Log|website=sports-reference.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> In 1993 Martin was selected in the All-[[Great Midwest Conference]] Second Team.<ref>''2016\u201317 Cincinnati Basketball Media Guide'', 2016, p. 55.</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n<ref name=card>Career summary and college stats as per Erik Martin's trading card for the 1992\u201393 Bearcats season.</ref>\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1989\u201390 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1989\u201390]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1989\u201390 TCU Horned Frogs men's basketball team|TCU]]\n| 29 || 7 || 15.2 || '''.681''' || '''.500''' || '''.587''' || 4.3 || '''1.4''' || 0.4 || '''0.7''' || 6.9\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1991\u201392 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1991\u201392]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1991\u201392 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team|Cincinnati]]\n| '''34''' || 0 || 16.4 || .525 || .000 || .561 || 4.0 || 1.0 || 0.9 || 0.5 || 6.3\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1992\u201393 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1992\u201393]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1992\u201393 Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball team|Cincinnati]]\n| 31 || '''31''' || '''27.1''' || .603 || .000 || .650 || '''6.7''' || '''1.4''' || '''1.5''' || 0.5 || 13.5\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | '''Career'''\n| align=\"left\" |\n| 94 || 38 || 19.6 || .597 || .250 || .611 || 5.0 || 1.3 || 1.0 || 0.5 || 8.9\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n== Professional career ==\nAfter the end of his senior season in 1993, Martin was automatically eligible for the [[1993 NBA draft]], but he was not drafted by an [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] franchise. He was selected by the [[Grand Rapids Hoops]] in the 2nd round (21st overall) of the 1993 [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]] draft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usbasket.com/cba/basketball-Draft_1993.asp|title=CBA Draft 1993|website=usbasket.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> On October 28, 1993 Martin signed a non-guaranteed one-year contract with the [[Golden State Warriors]] of the NBA, as a replacement for injured forward [[Chris Gatling]];<ref>{{Cite news|title=Warriors sign UC's Martin|date=October 29, 1993|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=41}}</ref> he was waived on November 2, and signed with the [[Yakima Sun Kings]] of the CBA.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Martin waived by Warriors|date=November 3, 1993|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=43}}</ref> In his rooke season in the CBA Martin played 55 games (22 starts), averaging 11.5 points and 5.6 rebounds per game, and also appeared in a playoff game, recording 14 points and 5 rebounds in 25 minutes of play.<ref name=cba>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbasketball/stats/p-martieri001|title=Erik Martin Statistics on StatsCrew.com|website=statscrew.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the season Martin was selected in the CBA All-Rookie First Team. For the following season Martin decided to stay with the Sun Kings, and appeared in 45 games with averages of 12.4 points, 5.4 rebounds, 1,8 assists, 1.4 steals and 1.7 blocks per game in 26 minutes per contest;<ref name=cba /> he was selected in the All-Defensive First Team and was the runner-up for Defensive Player of the Year, finishing behind [[Mike Bell (basketball)|Mike Bell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/2499307/cba-honors-bell|title=CBA Honors Bell|newspaper=[[The Daily Oklahoman]]|date=April 21, 1995|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the season the Sun Kings won the league title, and Martin averaged 9.8 points and 5.7 rebounds over 14 playoff games.<ref name=cba />\n\nIn the summer of 1995 Martin had shoulder surgery,<ref>{{Cite news|title=UC: Van Exel pays fines to play|date=June 1, 1995|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=56}}</ref> and did not play a single game during the 1995\u201396 CBA season.<ref name=cba /> Martin had then signed with the [[Fort Wayne Fury]], and was traded in June 1996 to the [[Omaha Racers]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=BASKETBALL|newspaper=The Daily News|date=June 27, 1996|page=16}}</ref> With the new team Martin found increased playing time, starting 22 of 47 games and averaging 9.8 points, 5.6 rebounds, 1.9 assists and 1.3 steals per game. He also participated in postseason play, averaging 8 points and 4.6 rebounds over 9 games.<ref name=cba /> In 1997 Martin signed with the [[Idaho Stampede]], a new franchise that selected him during the 1997 CBA expansion draft in late May.<ref>{{Cite news|title=CBA|newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|date=May 29, 1997|page=194}}</ref> He started the season with the Stampede;<ref>{{Cite news|title=PROBABLE STARTING LINEUPS|date=November 29, 1997|newspaper=[[The Dispatch / The Rock Island Argus|The Dispatch]]|page=36}}</ref> after 10 games (9 starts) during which he averaged 8.2 points, 4.7 rebounds and a career-high 3.2 assists per game,<ref name=cba /> Martin joined the [[La Crosse Bobcats]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=CBA AMERICAN CONFERENCE|newspaper=[[La Crosse Tribune]]|date=January 31, 1998|page=20}}</ref> and played 35 games with the team, averaging 6.5 points and 4.9 rebounds.<ref name=cba /> Towards the end of the season he joined the Yakima Sun Kings again, and played 5 regular season games and 5 playoff games.<ref name=cba />\n\nIn 2000 Martin played for the Luckipar Panthers in [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.taiwanhoops.com/2000/01/yulon-dominates-luckipar-gets-first-win.html|title=YULON DOMINATES ; LUCKIPAR GETS FIRST WIN |date=January 24, 2000|website=taiwanhoops.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> He then spent the 2000\u201301 season in [[Japan]] with [[Denso Hoop Gang]].<ref>{{Cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010217191129fw_/http://www.jbl.or.jp/teams/nl/n02denso_e.html|url=DENSO, Hoop Gang|website=jbl.or.jp|archivedate=February 17, 2001|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Martin played for the [[Seoul SK Knights]] for the [[2001\u201302 KBL season]] in [[South Korea]], averaging 14.8 points and 12.3 rebounds per game over 45 games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english.worldhoopstats.com/stats/kbl-kr/erik-martin-255050.html|title=Statistics from Erik Martin in KBL (South Korea)|website=worldhoopstats.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.donga.com/en/article/all/20011213/210123/1/Phoenix-Instead-of-Pheasant|title=Phoenix Instead of Pheasant|date=December 13, 2001|author=Kim, Sang-Ho|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asia-basket.com/South-Korea/basketball-League-KBL_2001-2002.asp|title=KBL 2001-2002|website=asia-basket.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== National team career ==\nMartin was called up for the [[United States men's national basketball team]] for the first time in 1995 for the [[Basketball at the 1995 Pan American Games|XII Pan American Games]] held in [[Mar del Plata]], [[Argentina]].<ref name=panam>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/pan-am-mens/twelfth-pan-american-games-1995.aspx|title=TWELFTH PAN AMERICAN GAMES -- 1995|date=June 10, 2010|website=usab.com|access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref> The US national team was put together by [[Mike Thibault]] and included only players from the [[Continental Basketball Association]], an American minor league: Martin was playing for the [[Yakima Sun Kings]] at the time,<ref name=panam /> and had just [[List of Continental Basketball Association champions|won the 1994\u201395 CBA season]] with the team. During the competition Martin played 7 games, and averaged 7.7 points and 3.9 rebounds, shooting 75.8% from the field (second on the team behind [[Mike Williams (basketball)|Mike Williams]]).<ref name=panam /> At the end of the Pan American Games the United States won the silver medal, having lost the final game to [[Argentina national basketball team|Argentina]], despite Martin's 15 points and 8 rebounds.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Record medal haul for U.S.|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|date=March 27, 1995|page=20}}</ref>\n\nMartin received a second call-up for Team USA in 1997, and was included in the team that participated in the [[1997 Tournament of the Americas]] in [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]].<ref name=americas>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usab.com/history/national-team-mens/fiba-americas-championship-1997.aspx|title=FIBA Americas Championship -- 1997|date=December 15, 2010|website=usab.com|access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref> Again, the team was formed by CBA players, and Martin was a member of the [[Idaho Stampede]] roster at the time. Martin played all 9 games during the competition, averaging 3.3 points and 2.8 rebounds per game, led the team in blocks with a total of 9 (tied with [[Michael McDonald (basketball)|Michael McDonald]]), and won the gold medal.<ref name=americas /> Martin ended his career in the national team with 16 total caps over a period of 2 years.\n\n== Coaching career ==\nAfter the end of his professional career as a player, Martin took up coaching. He started in 2003 at Jacobs Center High School in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], and had the double role of head coach of the junior varsity team and assistant coach for the varsity team for one season.<ref name=kstate>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kstatesports.com/news/2006/8/21/5583df09e4b06b726e6645ef_131478088935182038.aspx|title=Huggins completes staff with Erik Martin|date=August 21, 2006|website=kstatesports.com|access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> He then joined the coaching staff of [[Cincinnati State Technical and Community College]] as an assistant to head coach Andre Tate, and spent two years in the position.<ref name=kstate /> In August 2006 he joined [[Bob Huggins]]' staff at [[Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball|Kansas State]] for the [[2006\u201307 Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball team|2006\u201307 season]], on his first position in a [[NCAA Division I]] program.<ref name=kstate /> When Huggins took up the head coach position at [[West Virginia Mountaineers men's basketball|West Virginia]], Martin followed him: he has been working as an assistant coach since the [[2007\u201308 West Virginia Mountaineers men's basketball team|2007\u201308 season]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[